    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overflow in F1AP setup request handling\n\n### Summary\nThe F1AP interface management code contained a critical buffer overflow vulnerability in the `cp_f1ap_setup_request` function and related copy/decode functions. The issue occurred when processing setup requests with more cells than the statically allocated arrays could hold, leading to out-of-bounds memory writes.\n\nThis could result in memory corruption and \"type confusion where a pointer is cast to an incompatible struct type downstream\" as observed in some deployment scenarios. The bug was particularly problematic when handling gNB-DU configuration updates with large cell lists.\n\nThe vulnerability was introduced during the initial implementation when bounds checking was not properly enforced for array accesses in the F1AP message copying functions.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/F1AP/lib/f1ap_interface_management.c`: Added bounds checking to prevent buffer overflows in all F1AP copy and decode functions\n  - `cp_f1ap_setup_request`: Added validation for `num_cells_available` against `F1AP_MAX_NB_CELLS`\n  - `cp_f1ap_du_configuration_update`: Added bounds checking for all cell arrays\n  - `cp_f1ap_du_configuration_update_acknowledge`: Added bounds checking for cell activation arrays  \n  - `cp_f1ap_cu_configuration_update_acknowledge`: Added bounds checking for cells, TNL associations, and UE lists\n  - `cp_f1ap_reset` and `cp_f1ap_reset_ack`: Added bounds checking for UE arrays\n  - All corresponding decode functions: Added bounds validation when setting array counts from ASN.1 decoded data\n\n### Reproduction\nThe issue can be triggered by sending an F1AP Setup Request or gNB-DU Configuration Update message with more cells than `F1AP_MAX_NB_CELLS` (currently 2). Under high load conditions with multiple concurrent connections, this leads to:\n- Memory corruption in adjacent data structures\n- Segmentation faults in downstream processing functions\n- Incorrect behavior where pointers are interpreted as incompatible struct types\n- Potential crashes in the RRC layer when processing corrupted F1AP messages\n\nThe bug manifests most consistently when the gNB is processing multiple DU connections simultaneously and one DU sends a malformed setup request with an excessive number of served cells.\n"
}